I did some more problem isolation with Axis2 code generation using the custom JRE.  I confirmed that when the problem occurs (when using Axis2 v1.2 runtime JARs), the "transformer" object being return is null in the following code segment:

import javax.xml.transform.Transformer;
import javax.xml.transform.TransformerFactory;

public class XSLTTemplateProcessor {
..

public static void parse(OutputStream out,
                             Document document,
                             InputStream xsltStream,
                             URIResolver customResolver,
                             boolean pretty)
            throws TransformerFactoryConfigurationError, TransformerException {
...
TransformerFactory transformerFactory = TransformerFactory.newInstance();
Transformer transformer = transformerFactory.newTransformer(xsltSource);
}
..
}


I also confirmed that when the wizard seems to be hanging for 2 to 3 minutes, it is in the XSLTTemplateProcessor class when trying to get newTransformer.  After taking a long time to get the transformer, most of the time, it would eventually be successful in getting a transformer.  On the second generation of Axis2 client in the same project, it would be taking a long time to generate a few of the files and then on the 6th file, it would return null for the transformer. 

Note that I did not see null being returned for newTransformer when using Axis2 v1.3.  However, I still see the delay in getting a transformer.  It did hang for a shorter duration though (may be 1 to 2 minutes).  This used to take about 10 seconds with other JREs.

Lahiru, are you aware of changes in Axis2 between v1.2 to v1.3 in this area of XSLTemplateProcessor?  I compared the two versions of classes and the code is identical.  Is there anything you could think of that could explain the difference in behavior betwen Axis2 v1.2 and v1.3?  I am also chasing this problem with the provider of the custom JRE but thought you might be able to shed some light on this problem from the Axis2 side.

We found out that we could not just set 

-Djavax.xml.transform.TransformerFactory=org.apache.xalan.processor.TransformerFactoryImpl

with the adoptor product that uses the custom JRE since this class is not in the SUN JRE and the adoptor product has to be able to run with both the custom JRE and the SUN JRE.

So the other alternative is to set the system property programmatically before using the XSLT processor.  I found that if I add the following to Axis2CoreFacetInstallDelegate, then it would work for both SUN JRE and the custom JRE.

try {
   Class.forName("org.apache.xalan.processor.TransformerFactoryImpl");
   System.setProperty("javax.xml.transform.TransformerFactory", "org.apache.xalan.processor.TransformerFactoryImpl");
}
catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
   // Do nothing.  Just leave as default.
}

I'll attach a patch shortly.
